node.text:
Relationships are so nuanced, each of us have our own paths with our own lessons to learn and this can be incredibly confusing sometimes when we are trying to find our footing.

I spend a lot of time working with people who are emerging from very unhealthy relationships or completely rewiring their relationship patterns. It is so important that we include a re-education of what healthy relationships look like as we embark on the healing journey, and that we remember that healthy relationships are not perfect relationships.

It is indeed OK to disagree and it is OK to have conflict from time to time, and it is even OK to do conflict poorly once in a while provided that the major boundaries of physical and emotional safety aren’t crossed and that we are able to repair, apologize, and commit to evolving our communication styles as we grow.

These are nine signs of a healthy and normal relationship. Are you in a relationship like this now? If so tag your partner and share gratitude for them. Is this the kind of relationship you are calling in? Tag a friend. 💕

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

May be an image of text that says 'No one knows the truth of your relationship better than you do, so no one can really tell you whether you should stay or go. However, it can help to receive reflections on what's considered healthy and normal in partnership so you can assess your reality more clearly. Conflict in relationship is normal, and can even be a sign that both people are honoring themselves by being willing to disagree and speak up when there's a misalignment.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'While it's normal to have disagreements and even bump into each other's ego's from time to time, it's not ok to be emotionally or physically abusive. Because we aren't taught how to remain in connection with other's during conflict, we may treat it like a war- we fight to be heard, to be right, to be seen, and we forget to listen. We may also be overcome by our wounds (fear of abandonment) and blame, attack, or act out.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Having reoccurring conflicts in a relationship isn't necessarily a sign that you shouldn't be together, but it is a sign that you may need outside support to see what this conflict really represents for you. More often than not, couples fight about "nothing" when deep down, there's a core wound from childhood asking to be healed. Healthy and happy couples choose to explore their own minds and emotional landscape so they can be better partners.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Relationship is the perfect storm to bring up all of our stuff, so it's completely normal to experience challenges and it's also normal to get help- couples therapy, courses, reading books together etc. Most of us attract partners who are different from us in many ways- and that makes sense, we're human. Even our friends tend to have opposing qualities to us. Being different isn't the problem, it's that we try to make our partners be just like us.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Rather than asking if you're "compatible" which you likely are in some ways and not in others, the better questions to pose are: Do we have the emotional toolbox to navigate what's coming up here? Do we both enjoy the chemistry and connection we have? Do we really want this to work? Are we willing to take on a challenge together and get help? Do we share a common vision for our partnership?'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'In a healthy partnership, conflict isn't explosive It's not unsafe for anyone involved, and it doesn't leave lasting wounds of betrayal behind. That said, when we're coming up against our childhood wounds, we may feel easily betrayed or abandoned by our partners even if that's not the heart of what's actually going on. This is when it can be really helpful to spend some time alone reality checking the situation. Journaling and working with a guide can help.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of text that says 'Sometimes couples go through very intense times together and things don't look "healthy" but can still get through it. Usually, this takes outside support, individual work like somatic therapy and a really strong desire to evolve the relationship. Othertimes, there's one person who's just not ready to do the work in relationship. They might think relationships are supposed to be easy or always give them butterflies and there's really nothing one can do to make a person in this mindset shift more quickly.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 02, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'In long- term relationships life happens and this impacts us -people get ill, we experience loss, financial stress, births, children, all of the things. We cannot expect relationships to be exciting and constantly stimulating. But there's a balance. In a healthy relationship, there's a commitment to coming back to love, and there's a feeling of being safe and connected even when times are tough. And overtime, conflict styles evolve and get better, not worse in other words, the relationship matures.'.

Ceremony and Ritual connect us back to spirit, to ourselves and to our communities. I was reminiscing and felt called to share some special moments from our 2019 wedding with you. 

When @EvolvingMan and I married, we wove in both of our ancestral lineages into the ceremony .  The photos show a few of the rituals we brought in and shared with our loved ones.

Ancestral totems and objects were brought by each guest. Some brought photos of their ancestors, or objects that represented their lineage to create an altar.

Each guest who entered the space was ceremonially smudged and welcomed. We had a circle of chairs surrounding the outside rows for elder guests, teachers and parents and fluffy rugs and pillows in the center for everyone else to gather comfortably.

Rather than being given away - a tradition rooted in agricultural times, we chose to walk toward each other from opposite sides of the ceremony space, symbolizing equality in our partnership.

We invited each guest to bring a gift -  something that carried a special meaning or symbol for them and to wrap it with a little note inside with their name. All of the gifts were placed in the middle of the room and before dinner, everyone intuitively selected a gift from the center of the room and then went to find the person whose item they had received to learn the story behind it. Such beautiful synchronicities happened with this one!

As part of our ceremony, after our vows we sat down with a large woven basket. Our friends and family came one by one, offering words, love notes, gifts of fresh flowers and sacred items.

Parents and elders received a gift of a blanket and were honored for their role in our lives.

There was no alcohol at our wedding, since neither of us drink. Our friends from @harmonic_arts brought in herbal exlirs, and we served raw cacao beans dipped in honey, and hot cacao.

Raw chocolate meditation by @glowchocolatelove mid-ceremony brought us all together and opened our hearts in preparation for a dance party! We ended the night with a forest walk.

There were so many more rituals we wove in, in collaboration with our ceremonialist @redmoonmysteryschool 

📷 @sararogersphotography

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The power struggle phase can happen quickly upon meeting someone (almost no honeymoon phase at all) especially in a trauma-bond or it can come after a year or two in relationship. Entering this phase can feel like coming down from a high. We might notice things we don't like about our partner more, feel triggered by things they say or do, or even question the relationship and think the love is gone because we don't feel the same intensity as in the beginning.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'We weren't taught that it's normal for the Honeymoon phase to end so when we hit a bump in the road we think something is wrong. In reality, all relationships go through growth phases and there are usually some mountains to climb before relaxing into a connected and soul-fulfilling Conscious Partnership. It can take years and years of work before a couple really lands in a place of mutual freedom, truth and liberation together.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The power struggle phase is a very tender time in a relationship because both people are usually coming head to head with their past wounds and deepest fears. When there's a lack of awareness, the relationship usually turns to chaos both people projecting their anger and hurt at one another, blaming and demanding. It can be exhausting and erode the relationship beyond repair. But there is an alternative path if both people are committed to growth.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'With a commitment to elf-awareness and healing, triggers in a relationship become opportunities for a couple to turn towards each other rather than against each other. They become allies in one another's healing journey. If this willingness isn't there and we see our partner as our enemy or make our conflicts about winning being right, then the power struggle phase will likely turn the relationship sour until it comes to an end'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Be careful not to shame yourself for your past relationship endings We are all learning and gathering wisdom along the way. Not all relationships are meant to last. Some are designed to awaken new sides of ourselves, to highlight where we need to heal. When we have a history of toxic relationships, it's usually because we have unhealed wounds from our history that haven't been addressed. This 1S a call for self-compassion.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Being Asleep in the Power Struggle: Conflict is avoided, or we engage to win and be right. We make each other responsible for how we feel and behave. We make blanket statements and assume the worst of our partners intentions. We withhold, shut-down, punish or blame. We project, call names, attack or criticize. We self abandon, caretake, enable or collapse in the relationship.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Being Awake in the Power Struggle: •Conflict is an opportunity for deeper healing. We are both responsible for our own emotions and behaviors. We get curious and ask questions rather than assuming or making up stories. We practice repair, accountability and connection. We don't call names, attack or punish each other. We practice staying connected to ourselves even when there's disagreement.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Can a Power Struggle Relationship Transform? Virtually all relationships will go through some form of power struggle. If we have the tools and emotional awareness, we will likely have the ability to navigate the storm into calm waters. If one or both people are not willing to be responsible for their internal reality, that also won't work. We should never blame ourselves for the times where things didn't work out, but we can always learn something.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Το create a healthy partnership, both people must be fully accountable for their reactions and have a desire to grow together. One person cannot do all of the work. It's also ok if both people have the awareness but don't have the desire. Not every partnership is meant to last. But when a couple has the chemistry and a deep willingness they can absolutely evolve and mature together and eventually find themselves in a flourishing, energizing and alive relationship.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The honeymoon phase doesn't even come close to the level of bliss a couple can experience when they commit to doing the work and co- creating a partnership that is rooted in truth.'.

node.text:
Shifting our attention from the external to the internal is foundational to building self-awareness and doing the inner-work. 

We can learn a lot about ourselves and where we are being asked to grow when we practice self-inquiry.

As always, many of these questions are nuanced and the whole picture cannot be fit into a tiny caption.

Notice how you feel in your body with each question that’s relevant to you and pause to really be with it. You may choose to take some of these questions and journal them to go deeper.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "How do I stop attracting unavailable partners? Also ask: "Do fear closeness? What part of myself stays hidden by choosing unavailable people." Insight: Attachment dynamics are nuanced and cannot be fit into a tiny caption, however we can practice being aware of ourselves and how we may be avoiding intimacy by choosing unavailable people.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "Do they make me feel safe?" Also ask: "Does my body know how to feel safe?" Insight: Safety is an inside job and a relational one. If our nervous systems are dysregulated, no one will be able to change that if you don't do the work. It's perfectly reasonable to want safety from a partner and it's equally important that you take responsibility for your own healing.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "Do they make me feel seen?" Also ask: "Am I afraid to be seen? Do let people see me?" Insight: Our wound will often act as gate- keeper to intimacy We may want people to break down our walls but in addition to having a willing partner, being seen requires our openness and the courage to be vulnerable.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "How do get my partner to do the work?" Also ask: "Am I waiting for my partner to do the work before open/show up/be vulnerable." Insight: We cannot force a person to do the work. If we're waiting for them to go first, we're making our growth their responsibility All we can do is lead with our hearts and commit to showing up fully, the rest will make itself known.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "Where are all the good/ conscious people?" Also ask: "Am I avoiding connection by making myself better than others?" Insight: We'll certainly meet people who are at a different leg of their journey and sometimes it's simply not a match. However if we are consistently finding that we are "more spiritual or conscious" than everyone we meet, our ego might be in the way. Practice being curious about others.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "Should I end my relationship?" Also ask: "Do we both truly want this relationship? Have we both demonstrated willingness to be accountable for our own emotions, behaviours and wounds?" Insight: No one outside of you can tell you what's right for you. Sometimes, we don' need to end it, we need to do the work- with the caveat that both partners must want the same thing.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "Why do partners always make me feel this way?" Also ask: "What does this feeling remind me of? When was the first ime felt this way" Insight: When we use "always" and "never" to describe our emotional reality, we know the wound is at the wheel. Instead of making it all someone else's fault, go to the root there's a core wound here asking for your love.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "Why don't they ever show up for me/ meet my needs?" Also ask: "Am communicating clearly from my heart, or criticizing, making demands or withholding?" Insight: When we feel undernourished in life. our relationships will reflect this. Our partners cannot meet all of our needs but it's realistic to expect that we feel more met than ignored. However, if we have a story that no one ever shows up for us, we might have some work to do around receiving love and letting it in.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Self-Awareness Work When asking: "I'm anxious, my partner is avoidant how do encourage them to change?" Also ask: Am directing all of my energy toward how they need to change and ignoring my own growth path?" Insight: the Anxious- Avoidant dance can shift if both partners are willing. This requires immense patience and can take many years. The anxious partner needs to practice self- soothing, work and giving space, the avoidant person needs to practice building internal safety and leaning into relationship more.'.

Photo by Rising Woman on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says '"How can Self-Awareness Work When asking: get my partner to be more like me?" Also ask: "Am fighting for sameness rather than embracing the gifts my partner can bring?" Insight: Opposites attract, and while we may draw in partners who we share common interests with, we'll likely be very different in many ways too. We can see this as problem, or we can recognize that when we combine our gifts and unique ways of thinking and being, we create a powerful team that can accomplish anything together!'.

node.text:
Slide through for the full convo.

All relationships have their challenges - so please note that in this series I’m not talking about variations of normal ups and downs.

I'm specifically speaking to roller-coaster relationships that are often built entirely off of trauma-bonding and involve a lot of game playing, chaos, manipulation and unsafe or extremely insecure dynamics where there’s really nothing other than two people projecting their pain at one another.

When we feel unbearable passion or intensity toward another person and convince ourselves that we have to ride it out because they are our soul mate, we’re really just hanging on to a false narrative that allows us to ride the temporary high but keeps us chained in a painful and limiting spot.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

Around the circle are 10 stones to represent 10 moons, Jessica's dharma path as a birth worker and profound teacher. All around them are more flowers, representing her friends and family, and then all of the pinecones enclosing the circle, sealed with dried rose petals represent her extended community, students, and clients - everyone impacted by her work who is holding her in their hearts forever. The ferns in all four directions weave us all together, hugged by the strength and protection of cedar - a symbol of the courage it takes to open our hearts and allow for grief to move through us. 🌊

This life is a precious one. It was a true gift to be in your presence Jessica, and to witness such devotion in another being. You have left this world better than you found it, and I have no doubt that your soul work continues on now.

Some relationships are meant to end, and some are simply meant to die in their current form to make room for the next chapter, together.'.

node.text:
There are many valid reasons for a relationship ending. Sometimes it’s not possible to transform the current partnership into something new because the entire foundation is cracked or was never there to begin with. Breakups are medicine too.

But there are also times where we are being called to lean in and let the partnership shape us, strip us of our illusions and rebirth us time and time again.

A Conscious Partnership doesn’t hold the other to a fixed reality, it makes space for each partner to die and rebirth a thousand times. Each time, coming back with more authenticity, more awareness, more vulnerability and truth.

Allowing our partners to change and celebrating their growth is the only way to keep energy and passion alive.

When we hold back our truth or hold on too tight to who we think a person is, we close the door on magic.

But when we remain open, express our desires, embody the energy we yearn for in our partnership and praise each other for the little and monumental shifts that occur over the years - the relationship only gets better with time.

Questions or thoughts?

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana

node.text:
All of the less than/better than projections need to be put to bed before we can truly embody the work.

Anyone who enters the space as a teacher or leader in any way will have to watch our for the distortion and inflated sense of self-importance that can come along with getting a lot of attention or having a big following count.

Similarly, we also have to watch out for the “I’m not good enough” story if we don’t have one. Some of the most gifted healers I’ve met have no social media following at all - who cares!

When we claim our gifts and step into service from truth, it’s not about celebrity status or being seen. It’s about heart connection. It’s about impact and dharma.

No one is above or below any of us. The quality of our hearts isn’t rooted in whether we are externally validated or recognized - it’s expressed in how we show up for ourselves, our families and those who surround us.

🌿 @sheleanaaiyana
